Go 101
A Practical Introduction for University Students
Tags: go, programming, beginner

* Why Does Go Exist?

The year is 2007. Rob Pike is waiting *45 minutes* for a C++ program to compile at Google.

While waiting, he attends a talk about *35 new features* coming to C++11, and asks himself:

_"Did the C++ committee really believe that what was wrong with C++_
_was that it didn't have enough features?"_

By the time that build finished, he, *Robert* *Griesemer*, and *Ken* *Thompson* had a whiteboard full of ideas.

That whiteboard became *Go*.

- Born inside Google in 2007
- Open-sourced in 2009
- Go 1.0 released in 2012 — backwards-compatible ever since

* What Go Set Out to Fix

Every mainstream language before Go had real pain points:

- *C* */* *C++* — fast, but unsafe, complex, slow to compile, manual memory management
- *Java* */* *C#* — safe, but verbose, heavy runtimes, slow startup, lots of ceremony
- *Python* */* *Ruby* */* *JavaScript* — friendly, but slow and weak at real concurrency
- *All* *of* *them* — concurrency is hard, dependency management is painful

Go's answer in one line:

  Fast like C, safe like Java, simple like Python — with concurrency built in.

What you get:

- Compiles in *seconds*, not minutes
- One *single* *binary* — no runtime, no JVM, no interpreter to install
- Goroutines and channels for easy concurrency
- Garbage collection, memory safety, and a strong standard library

* Go's Family Tree

.html code/family_tree.html

Go is the first mainstream language to merge *two* language traditions — European simplicity (left) and American systems/concurrency (right).

That is why in Go:

- Declarations read left-to-right: `name type` (from *Oberon*, not C)
- Goroutines and channels feel natural (from Hoare's *CSP*, 1978)
- Implicit interfaces mirror a 1989 HP Labs paper — rediscovered, not invented

* What is a Go Program?

Every Go program has a shape. Before learning the details, learn to read it.

- Every file belongs to a *package*
- The `main` package is special — it produces a runnable program
- `main()` is always the starting point
- Names starting with a capital letter are *exported* (visible outside the package)

* Hello, 世界

.play code/hello.go

* Anatomy of a Go Program

.html code/anatomy.html

- `package main` tells Go this is a runnable program
- `import "fmt"` brings in the format package
- `fmt.Println` is exported — that is why it starts with a capital letter

* Functions

.code code/functions.go

- Functions are the building blocks of Go programs
- Parameters have types after their names
- Multiple return values are common in Go

* How Do We Store Data?

Go is *statically typed* — every variable has a type, known at compile time.

- `var` declares a variable
- `:=` is shorthand inside functions (type is inferred)
- Every type has a *zero value* — Go never leaves memory uninitialised

* Variables and Types

.code code/variables.go

Basic types you will use most:

  int      float64      bool      string

* Zero Values

.code code/zerovalues.go

No surprises. Go sets every variable to a sensible default.

- `int` → `0`
- `float64` → `0.0`
- `bool` → `false`
- `string` → `""`

* Constants and Type Conversions

.code code/constants.go

- Constants are fixed at compile time
- Go does *not* freely mix number types — you must convert explicitly

* How Do We Make Decisions?

`for` is Go's only loop. `if` and `switch` handle branching.

Go keeps the control flow vocabulary small — but it covers everything you need.

* For — Go's Only Loop

.code code/forloop.go

Three forms:

- C-style: `for i := 0; i < 5; i++`
- While-style: `for n < 100`
- Infinite: `for { ... }`

* If and Switch

.code code/ifsw.go

- `switch` is cleaner than a long chain of `if/else`
- Cases do not fall through by default in Go

* How Do We Store Many Values?

.html code/collections_intro.html

- *Array* — fixed size, rarely used directly
- *Slice* — dynamic, used everywhere in real Go code
- *Map* — key-value storage

* Arrays and Slices

.code code/slices.go

Arrays have a fixed size. Slices are flexible views over data.

In real Go code, you will almost always use slices.

* How a Slice Works

.html code/slice_diagram.html

* Range

.code code/range.go

`range` iterates over slices, arrays, maps, and strings.

- First value: index (or key)
- Second value: element (or value)

* Maps

.code code/maps.go

- Key-value data
- Access a missing key returns the zero value
- Use the two-value form to check if a key exists

* How Do We Model Real-World Data?

A *struct* groups related fields into one named type.

.code code/structs.go

Good examples for students:

  Student   Book   BankAccount   CartItem

* A Struct is a Labeled Box

.html code/struct_diagram.html

* How Do We Add Behaviour?

*Methods* are functions attached to a type. This is how Go adds behaviour to data.

.code code/methods.go

Go has no classes. Structs + methods cover the same ground, more simply.

* Interfaces

An *interface* describes behaviour, not structure.

.code code/interfaces.go

- Any type that has the right methods satisfies the interface automatically
- No `implements` keyword needed
- Keep interfaces small — one or two methods is normal in Go

_Fun_ _fact:_ Go's implicit interfaces closely match a 1989 HP Labs paper the Go team didn't know about — great ideas tend to be rediscovered.

* Many Types → One Interface

.html code/interface_diagram.html

* How Does Go Handle Memory?

*Pointers* store the address of a value. They let functions modify data without copying it.

.code code/pointers.go

The clearest way to teach pointers:

1. Show a function that *fails* to modify a variable (passes by value)
2. Show the pointer version that *works*

* Pointers, Visually

.html code/pointer_diagram.html

* How Does Go Handle Problems?

Go does not rely on exceptions. Errors are *returned values*.

.code code/errors.go

- Functions often return `(value, error)`
- Always check `err != nil` before using the value
- `defer` runs a statement when the surrounding function returns

* Mini Project: Todo List

Build a small in-memory Todo app using basic Go concepts:

- `struct` + methods
- slices and loops
- error handling
- small, focused functions

Project folder:

- `present/project/todo`

Run project tests:

`go test ./present/project/todo`

* Todo Project Preview

.code project/todo/todo.go

* Go's Design Philosophy

A few ideas shaped the entire language:

- _"As simple as possible, but not simpler."_
- _"When in doubt, leave it out."_ — Josh Bloch
- Tony Hoare: there are two ways to build software — make it so simple there are obviously no bugs, or so complex there are no obvious bugs. *Go chose the first.*

The Go team's default answer to new features is *no*.

  Saying "no" is temporary. Saying "yes" is forever.

That is why Go is small on purpose:

- *25* keywords (Java has ~50, C++ has ~90)
- One loop (`for`), one way to format code (`gofmt`), one way to manage deps (`go` `mod`)
- The language you learn today will still be valid in ten years

